# AW Analysis — Cursor Rules
# This file is prepended to every Cursor conversation in this repo.
# Keep it specific to the project. Generic Python rules go elsewhere.

## Project
You are working on AW Analysis, a cross-asset market intelligence platform
covering equities, crypto, forex, and commodities. The codebase is a
self-directed AI Systems Engineering study programme with 8 modules of
production-quality exercises.

## Stack
- Python 3.14 (use `PYTHONPATH=$(pwd)` for cross-module imports — this is
  required, not optional, due to Python 3.14's changed default sys.path)
- Anthropic SDK (pin anthropic>=0.40) — this is the only LLM provider
- Claude Haiku 4.5 for cheap/fast tasks, Claude Sonnet 4 for quality tasks
- ChromaDB for vector storage (prototyping), pgvector (production target)
- Voyage AI for embeddings (voyageai SDK)
- Langfuse for observability (langfuse>=3.0.0)
- colorama for coloured terminal output in exercises

## Style
- British English in all comments, docstrings, documentation, and READMEs
  (tokenisation, behaviour, optimise, colour, etc.)
- Fully typed function signatures using standard library types
- Prefer dataclasses over dicts for structured data
- Prefer explicit imports over wildcard imports
- No type: ignore comments — fix the type instead
- Keep functions under 40 lines; extract helpers if longer
- Docstrings on public functions; skip them on obvious private helpers

## Patterns — DO follow
- The agent loop pattern from module-3 (explicit while loop with tool dispatch)
  is the reference. Do not reimplement it; extend it.
- The provider abstraction from module-7 (Protocol + per-provider impl) is the
  reference for any new abstraction layer. Extend it, don't replace it.
- The EmissionBackend protocol from module-8 exercise 8.2 is the observability
  pattern. New backends implement emit() and flush().
- The two-layer eval pattern from module-6 (deterministic check + LLM-as-judge)
  is how we grade outputs. Do not skip the deterministic layer.
- Use pip3 not pip (macOS convention)
- Use bare `git commit` to open the editor for multi-line commit messages

## Patterns — DO NOT
- Do not add LangChain, LlamaIndex, or other heavyweight frameworks as
  dependencies. We stay on the Anthropic SDK and write our own loops.
- Do not add dependencies without justifying them in the commit message.
- Do not refactor existing modules unless explicitly asked.
- Do not add comments that restate what the code does.
- Do not use `python` — always use `python3`.
- Do not use `-m` flag for multi-line commit messages (shell metacharacter
  issues on macOS). Use bare `git commit` instead.
- Do not create virtual environments unless specifically asked — the exercises
  use system Python with --break-system-packages.

## File conventions
- Each exercise lives in its own folder under the module directory
- Every exercise has a README.md with actual run results (not "expected output")
- requirements.txt per exercise, not a global one
- Tests go in the exercise folder alongside the module being tested

## Models (current as of April 2026)
- Haiku: claude-haiku-4-5-20251001 (cheap judge, easy-class routing)
- Sonnet: claude-sonnet-4-20250514 (default for quality tasks)
- Opus: claude-opus-4-20250514 (reserved for genuinely hard tasks)
- Note: claude-3-haiku and claude-3-5-haiku are RETIRED — do not use them